Hey guys, I have another plug and play solution for y’all today. If you’ve worked in web development for any period of time, chances are you’ve been asked to implement an accordion in a webpage or app at some point. For most working developers, this means reaching for a solution that’s wrapped in a framework or component library. There’s absolutely nothing wrong with that and there are many fantastic solutions out there. However, there are times when general solutions don’t cut it and you have to switch to manual.
For those who aren’t familiar with accordions, effectively they are buttons or headers which trigger a panel of text or other functionality to be shown. Their main purpose is to hide and show extra information in order to prevent clutter on a webpage. Depending on what you’re building, there could be any amount of extra functionality you might want to add to a component like this.
When building UI components with frameworks like Angular, I’m a big fan of solutions that have three qualities:

• It’s plug and play

• It can easily be replaced with something more substantial

• It can be easily customizable
Anyone who’s worked on a project of a period of time can tell you with certainty that the true cost of software comes when you need to maintain it, not when you first build it. Thus, when adding new code, maintainability should be at the forefront of a developer’s mind. Maintainability is a huge topic so I won’t write too much about it here, but I’ve come to believe that the easier a UI component can be replaced, the easier the project it’s apart of can be maintained. This is because, in my experience, businesses often like to make changes you can’t anticipate to their look, brand, and adopt new technology they think will get them ahead.
Without further ado, here’s the code for a plug and play accordion Angular component. Copy, past, and customize with my complements! :)
import { Component, signal, WritableSignal } from '@angular/core';
import { NgClass } from '@angular/common';@Component({
selector: 'app-accordion',
imports: [NgClass],
styles: `
/* remove any native button styles */
.strip-button-styles {
background: none;
color: inherit;
border: none;
padding: 0;
font: inherit;
cursor: pointer;
outline: inherit;
}
.header {
background-color: #eee;
color: #222;
cursor: pointer;
padding: 2em;
width: 100%;
text-align: left;
transition: 0.4s;
}
.active,
.header:hover {
background-color: #ccc;
}
.body {
padding: 2em;
background-color: inherit;
overflow: hidden;
}
.show {
display: block;
}
.hide {
display: none;
}
`,
template: `
<!-- ng-content allows you to select html blocks using a CSS selector. Here we can use this
feature to select the template fragment we want for the header and body -->
<button
class="strip-button-styles header"
[ngClass]="{ active: expanded() }"
(click)="toggle()"
>
<ng-content select="[data-header]"></ng-content>
</button>
<div class="body" [ngClass]="{ show: expanded(), hide: !expanded() }">
<ng-content select="[data-body]"></ng-content>
</div>
`,
})
export class Accordion {
expanded: WritableSignal<boolean> = signal(false);
toggle() {
const val = !this.expanded();
this.expanded.update(() => val);
}
}
